## Purpose
Wire the StartupBanner into the server's startup sequence so it displays automatically when a FastMCP server starts. This is where all the rich console work becomes visible to users.

## Integration Point
The banner should display:
1. AFTER the server is fully initialized (all tools/resources/prompts registered)
2. AFTER the transport is ready
3. BEFORE entering the main message loop
4. ONLY if not suppressed via environment variable

## Code Changes Required

### In crates/fastmcp-server/src/lib.rs

```rust
use fastmcp_console::{console, banner::StartupBanner};

impl Server {
    pub fn run_stdio(self) -> ! {
        // Check if banner should be shown
        let show_banner = !std::env::var("FASTMCP_NO_BANNER")
            .map(|v| matches!(v.to_lowercase().as_str(), "1" | "true" | "yes"))
            .unwrap_or(false);

        // Display startup banner to humans (writes to stderr)
        if show_banner {
            StartupBanner::new(&self.info.name, &self.info.version)
                .description(self.instructions.as_deref().unwrap_or(""))
                .tools(self.router.tools_count())
                .resources(self.router.resources_count())
                .prompts(self.router.prompts_count())
                .transport("stdio")
                .render(console());
        }

        // Continue with normal stdio operation
        self.run_stdio_internal()
    }

    fn run_stdio_internal(self) -> ! {
        // ... existing implementation ...
    }
}
```

### Add Counter Methods to Router

The Router needs methods to count registered handlers:

```rust
// In crates/fastmcp-server/src/router.rs

impl Router {
    /// Get the number of registered tools
    pub fn tools_count(&self) -> usize {
        self.tools.len()
    }

    /// Get the number of registered resources
    pub fn resources_count(&self) -> usize {
        self.resources.len()
    }

    /// Get the number of registered prompts
    pub fn prompts_count(&self) -> usize {
        self.prompts.len()
    }
}
```

### Add Dependency to fastmcp-server Cargo.toml

```toml
[dependencies]
fastmcp-console = { path = "../fastmcp-console" }
```

## Why This Location?

### Why in run_stdio()?
- Called once at startup
- Has access to all server state
- Before the blocking message loop
- Easy to skip with environment variable

### Why Not in ServerBuilder::build()?
- Server might be used without stdio
- Other transports (SSE, WebSocket) may have different banners
- Better separation of concerns

### Why Not in main()?
- Would require passing counts separately
- Less ergonomic API
- Server knows its own capabilities

## Environment Variable: FASTMCP_NO_BANNER

Purpose: Allow users to suppress the banner entirely.

Use cases:
1. Agents that watch stderr and don't want extra output
2. Scripts that parse server output
3. Users who prefer minimal output
4. CI environments that want quiet startup

## Timing Considerations

The banner MUST render quickly:
- Should complete in < 10ms
- No network calls
- No file I/O (except terminal detection)
- No async operations

If the banner is slow, it delays the server becoming ready, which affects agent startup times.

## Error Handling

Banner rendering should NEVER crash the server:

```rust
if show_banner {
    // Wrap in catch_unwind for safety
    if let Err(e) = std::panic::catch_unwind(|| {
        StartupBanner::new(...)
            .render(console());
    }) {
        // Log but don't crash
        eprintln!("Warning: banner rendering failed: {:?}", e);
    }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Banner displays when server starts with stdio transport
- [ ] Banner is suppressed when FASTMCP_NO_BANNER=1
- [ ] Banner shows correct tool/resource/prompt counts
- [ ] Banner shows server name and version
- [ ] Banner shows instructions/description if set
- [ ] Router exposes count methods
- [ ] fastmcp-console is a dependency of fastmcp-server
- [ ] No panics from banner rendering can crash server

